    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kinda yellow and pale compared to the top ones. what's probably going on with them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic sign of nutrient deficiency, likely nitrogen, which is often the first to show up as yellowing at the base of the plant while the top remains vibrant. It's a very common issue, but you should also consider that your soil might be too dry or the plants are getting too crowded, causing them to compete for resources. Since you're growing tomatoes, they are heavy feeders, so you might want to consider adding some compost or a balanced fertilizer to the soil around the base of the plants. If the leaves continue to yellow and drop off, it could indicate a root problem, so check the soil moisture levels and ensure the roots aren't rotting. If you're still unsure, you could take a sample of the soil to a local extension office for a professional diagnosis. In the meantime, make sure to water the plants deeply but infrequently to encourage deep root growth. If the yellowing persists, you might want to prune off the affected lower leaves to improve air circulation and reduce the risk of disease. If you have any other questions about your tomato plants, feel free to ask!",
      "source": "target",
