      "content": "Ah, you caught me! I slipped up and compared the soil test to a goblin's treasure hunt because, well, sometimes soil pH feels like a hidden map that only the most resourceful (and slightly mischievous) goblins can decipher. It's a silly analogy, I know, but I can't help it when I think about how hard it is to find the right nutrients without a little bit of magical luck.\n\nAnyway, back to your tomatoes! Besides pH, there are a few other things that could be stealing those nutrients or blocking them from reaching your plants. First, **compaction** is a big one; if your soil is too hard, the roots can't get deep enough to find the nitrogen they need, even if it's sitting right there. Second, **over-fertilizing** with phosphorus or potassium can lock up the nitrogen, making it unavailable to the plant. Third, **root rot** from overwatering can damage the root system, preventing it from absorbing anything at all. Finally, **pests** like root maggots or nematodes can physically eat the roots, leaving the plant starved.\n\nSince you're planning to adjust the pH, make sure to do it gradually",
